movePath: fall back to recursive copy on EXDEV

rename(2) returns EXDEV for directory renames whose target parent is a
"merge"-type overlayfs directory when redirect_dir is disabled. The
overlay root is always merge-type (its dentry stack has both upper-root
and lower-root by construction). When overlayfs is mounted from inside a
user namespace (e.g. a Kubernetes pod with hostUsers:false), the kernel
forces redirect_dir=off and refuses redirect_dir=on, so this EXDEV is
unavoidable for any directory rename targeting the overlay root.

In a chroot-store setup (`--store local?root=...`), realStoreDir is the
overlay root; movePath's chroot-output -> realStoreDir/{out} rename hits
this for every directory output. moveFile()'s temp-then-rename fallback
hits the same EXDEV (its final rename also targets the overlay root),
so copy directly to dst instead. The path lock is held and the caller
deletePath()'d dst first, so the loss of atomicity is bounded.

--- a/src/libstore/unix/build/derivation-builder.cc
+++ b/src/libstore/unix/build/derivation-builder.cc
@@ -552,7 +552,13 @@ static void movePath(const Path & src, const Path & dst)
     if (changePerm)
         chmod_(src, st.st_mode | S_IWUSR);

-    std::filesystem::rename(src, dst);
+    try {
+        std::filesystem::rename(src, dst);
+    } catch (std::filesystem::filesystem_error & e) {
+        if (e.code().value() != EXDEV)
+            throw;
+        copyFile(std::filesystem::path(src), std::filesystem::path(dst), true);
+    }

     if (changePerm)
         chmod_(dst, st.st_mode);
